The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Metro | The City Diary
                                                                                                               The City Diary
                Two pedestrians died and one was injured in mishaps across the city on Sunday. A 45-year-old woman died after being knocked down by a Tata Sumo on Saturday night. Police said Arati Mondal and a neighbour were crossing Canal West Road near Narkeldanga when the car hit them. Both were taken to NRS hospital where Arati died. The driver has been arrested and the car impounded.  40-year-old pedestrian was injured after being run over by a minibus at the crossing of Beni Nandan Street and Asutosh Mukherjee Road in Bhowanipore on Sunday afternoon. Kali Prasad Chowbey, a junior officer in the public works department, was walking down the road when the minibus hit him from behind. Chowbey was taken to SSKM Hospital in a critical condition. The bus driver fled with the vehicle.  round 100 residents blocked the crossing to protest rash driving and lax policing. They also smashed the windscreen of another minibus. The situation was brought under control after a police contingent arrived on the spot.  n unidentified person, in his 50s, died after being hit by an unidentified vehicle near Metro cinema at 6.30pm on Saturday. The man was taken to Medical College and Hospital where he was declared dead.    A 23-year-old youth drowned in the Hooghly near Doltala Ghat in Uttarpara on Sunday afternoon. Sarmilan Das, a resident of Bhadrakali in Uttarpara, had gone to take a bath with a friend. The body has not been recovered yet.     Students ransacked a computer training centre in Sodepur on Sunday alleging that it did not have government recognition. The students alleged they had enrolled with the centre believing its claim in advertisements that it was recognised by the government. We have paid thousands to the centre but have now come to know that it does not have government approval to run any course, said a student. The centre authorities were unavailable for comment. Around 300 youths staged a demonstration outside the centre for two hours.    A 27-year-old youth carrying a single-shot was arrested from Alimuddin Street on Saturday evening. Mohammed Reazuddin could not give satisfactory replies to the queries of the cops.    Air Indias Calcutta-Guwahati flight returned to the parking bay before take-off on Sunday because of a snag. Airport officials said the flight, carrying 57 passengers, was scheduled to take off at 9.50am. The passengers boarded another aircraft that took off around 11.30am.     A bullet was seized from a 40-year-old passenger at the city airport on Sunday. Prem Chand Gupta, a resident of Uttar Pradesh, was carrying the bullet in his hand baggage. Gupta, who was to board IndiGos Calcutta-Goa flight, got the licence faxed from his residence but the bullet was seized and deposited to airport police station.    The result of the exams to fill up clerical posts in the state fire and emergency services department has been put up at the departments headquarters on Free School Street. The test was held on June 1, 2008.     Cash and jewellery worth Rs 1 lakh were looted from a flat on GT Road in Howrah on Saturday night. Police said the incident occurred when the owners were away.    The body of an unidentified man aged around 60 was found floating in a lake in Bamangachi, Howrah, on Sunday.            
